item.title: European Countries Move Closer to Reopening Continent
item.description: European governments are preparing to unlock the continent’s economy by introducing rules and guidelines that amount to a sweeping reconfiguration of everyday life, from subway seating to classroom size.

item.title: Protesters in Lebanon Demand Economic Relief
item.description: As Lebanon reopens after a pandemic lockdown, protesters have burst onto the streets to demand relief from the country’s deteriorating economy in one of the first signs of a violent backlash following weeks under quarantine.

item.title: South Korea's Playbook for Reopening: Don't Use Cash, Sit Side by Side
item.description: After two months of social distancing amid the coronavirus, South Korea is about to open up. And it has a rule for everything, hoping to keep people safe as they start returning to their regular routines.

item.title: Pressure Builds to Reopen Churches in Italy
item.description: Masses are still on hold, stirring a debate between religious liberty and public-health concern across Europe and the U.S.

item.title: Kim Jong Un's Absence Fits a Pattern of Secrecy Around His Family's Health
item.description: The health of North Korean leaders is among the isolated regime’s most closely guarded secrets—and something foreign intelligence agencies have struggled to keep tabs on.

item.title: Coronavirus Widens Europe's North-South Economic Divide
item.description: Most nations of Europe’s north are set to recover faster from their medically induced economic comas than those in the south, exacerbating a divergence of fortunes in the eurozone.
